{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"97e41753-2067-4ee5-90b1-a5d60841aeb1","content":"Here's the analysis of **EvalHeavy.csproj** — I found **3 evaluation performance anti-patterns**:\n\n---\n\n### 1. 🔴 File I/O Property Function (line 13)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nCalling `System.IO.File::ReadAllText()` during evaluation forces synchronous disk I/O on **every evaluation** (build, IDE load, IntelliSense). Move this to a target with `Inputs/Outputs` so it only runs at build-time when the file changes.\n\n### 2. 🔴 Expensive Recursive Glob (line 9)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` walks the **entire directory tree** at evaluation time. This gets progressively slower as the repo grows, especially if directories like `node_modules`, `.git`, or publish output exist. Narrow the glob to specific extensions or directories, and add heavy directories to `DefaultItemExcludes`.\n\n### 3. 🟡 Deep Import Chain (3 levels)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nEach import adds evaluation overhead. At 3 levels this is moderate, but it's worth flattening if these only set simple properties — they could be consolidated into a single `.props` file.\n\n---\n\n**Highest impact fix:** Remove the `File::ReadAllText` call from the `PropertyGroup` and replace the broad `**\\*.*` glob with a scoped pattern. These two changes alone would meaningfully reduce evaluation time.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"13f0d2a1-2404-4aa6-bd23-ecf1824a0607","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a full picture of the project. Let me analyze the evaluation performance issues:\n\n1. **Deep import chain**: `EvalHeavy.csproj` → `level1.props` → `level2.props` → `level3.props` — that's 3 levels deep. The skill guidance says >20 levels is concerning, so 3 levels is not terrible but it's a pattern to note.\n\n2. **Expensive glob pattern**: `<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />` — This is a broad recursive glob that walks the entire directory tree. \n\nThe real performance culprits are the file I/O property function that reads `build-notes.txt` during evaluation—a known anti-pattern—and the glob pattern that doesn't leverage `DefaultItemExcludes`, forcing manual exclusions instead of using the SDK's built-in optimization.","outputTokens":693,"requestId":"1415:8D0D7:61BEFC7:6D359F8:69EC1685"},"id":"79046e67-4522-4a35-bbc3-cc5251d8b58a","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:19:18.809Z","parentId":"973a64da-e75d-4d8d-ac40-77f7df69ca59"}
